#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:112
msgid "Modular output"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:114
msgid ""
"When using the WebIDL binder, often what you are doing is creating a "
"library. In that case, the `MODULARIZE` option makes sense to use. It wraps "
"the entire JavaScript output in a function, and returns a Promise which "
"resolves to the initialized Module instance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:125
msgid ""
"The promise is resolved when it is safe to run compiled code, i.e. after it "
"has been has been downloaded and instantiated. The promise is resolved at "
"the same time the `onRuntimeInitialized` callback is invoked, so there's no "
"need to use `onRuntimeInitialized` when using `MODULARIZE`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:130
msgid ""
"You can use the `EXPORT_NAME` option to change `Module` to something else. "
"This is good practice for libraries, as then they don't include unnecessary "
"things in the global scope, and in some cases you want to create more than "
"one."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:136
msgid "Using C++ classes in JavaScript"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:138
msgid ""
"Once binding is complete, C++ objects can be created and used in JavaScript "
"as though they were normal JavaScript objects. For example, continuing the "
"above example, you can create the ``Foo`` and ``Bar`` objects and call "
"methods on them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:149
msgid "Always access objects through the :ref:`module` object, as shown above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:151
msgid ""
"While the objects are also available in the global namespace by default, "
"there are cases where they will not be (for example, if you use the :term:"
"`closure compiler` to minify code or wrap compiled code in a function to "
"avoid polluting the global namespace). You can of course use whatever name "
"you like for the module by assigning it to a new variable: ``var "
"MyModuleName = Module;``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:153
msgid ""
"You can only use this code when it is :ref:`safe to call compiled code <faq-"
"when-safe-to-call-compiled-functions>`, see more details in that FAQ entry."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:155
msgid ""
"JavaScript will automatically garbage collect any of the wrapped C++ objects "
"when there are no more references. If the C++ object doesn't require "
"specific clean up (i.e. it doesn't have a destructor) then no other action "
"needs to be taken."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:157
msgid ""
"If a C++ object does need to be cleaned up, you must explicitly call :js:"
"func:`Module.destroy(obj) <Module.destroy>` to invoke its destructor — then "
"drop all references to the object so that it can be garbage collected. For "
"example, if ``Bar`` were to allocate memory that requires cleanup:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:165
msgid ""
"The C++ constructor is called transparently when a C++ object is created in "
"JavaScript. There is no way, however, to tell if a JavaScript object is "
"about to be garbage collected, so the binder glue code can't automatically "
"call the destructor."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:167
msgid ""
"You will usually need to destroy the objects which you create, but this "
"depends on the library being ported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:170
msgid "Attributes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:172
msgid ""
"Object attributes are defined in IDL using the ``attribute`` keyword. These "
"can then be accessed in JavaScript using either ``get_foo()``/``set_foo()`` "
"accessor methods, or directly as a property of the object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:195
msgid "For read-only attributes, see :ref:`webidl-binder-const`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:198
msgid "Pointers, References, Value types (Ref and Value)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:200
msgid ""
"C++ arguments and return types can be pointers, references, or value types "
"(allocated on the stack). The IDL file uses different decoration to "
"represent each of these cases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:202
msgid ""
"Undecorated argument and return values of a custom type in the IDL are "
"assumed to be *pointers* in the C++:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:214
msgid ""
"This assumption isn't true for base types like void,int,bool,DOMString,etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:216
msgid "References should be decorated using ``[Ref]``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:229
msgid ""
"If ``[Ref]`` is omitted on a reference, the generated glue C++ will not "
"compile (it fails when it tries to convert the reference — which it thinks "
"is a pointer — to an object)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:231
msgid ""
"If the C++ returns an object (rather than a reference or a pointer) then the "
"return type should be decorated using ``[Value]``. This will allocate a "
"static (singleton) instance of that class and return it. You should use it "
"immediately, and drop any references to it after use."
msgstr ""

