#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:420
msgid "Function overloads"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:422
msgid ""
"C++ allows function overloads, where multiple member functions have the same "
"name but different arguments. By default, the *WebIDL Binder* allows you to "
"bind overloaded functions if they differ only in the number of arguments:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:442
msgid ""
"If your overloaded functions differ in some other way (say, in the types) "
"then you can use the ``[BindTo]`` attribute to tell the tool what function "
"name to bind to (that is, to call):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:462
msgid ""
"In this case the C++ function ``test(const char*)`` will be named "
"``testString`` in JavaScript and ``test(int)`` will be named ``testInt``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:466
msgid ""
"You can also use ``[BindTo]`` to just rename a function, e.g. if you want to "
"rename ``MyFunctionName`` to ``myFunctionName``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:469
msgid "Pointers and comparisons"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:471
msgid ""
"All the binding functions expect to receive wrapper objects (which contain a "
"raw pointer) rather than a raw pointer. You shouldn't normally need to deal "
"with raw pointers (these are simply memory addresses/integers). If you do, "
"the following functions in the compiled code can be useful:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:473
msgid ""
"``wrapPointer(ptr, Class)`` — Given a raw pointer (an integer), returns a "
"wrapped object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:475
msgid ""
"If you do not pass the ``Class``, it will be assumed to be the root class — "
"this probably isn't what you want!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:477
msgid "``getPointer(object)`` — Returns a raw pointer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:478
msgid ""
"``castObject(object, Class)`` — Returns a wrapping of the same pointer but "
"to another class."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:479
msgid "``compare(object1, object2)`` — Compares two objects' pointers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:481
msgid ""
"There is always a *single* wrapped object for a certain pointer to a certain "
"class. This allows you to add data on that object and use it elsewhere using "
"normal JavaScript syntax (``object.attribute = someData`` etc.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:483
msgid ""
"``compare()`` should be used instead of direct pointer comparison because it "
"is possible to have different wrapped objects with the same pointer if one "
"class is a subclass of the other."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:488
msgid "NULL"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:490
msgid ""
"All the binding functions that return pointers, references, or objects will "
"return wrapped pointers. The reason is that by always returning a wrapper, "
"you can take the output and pass it to another binding function without that "
"function needing to check the type of the argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:492
msgid ""
"One case where this can be confusing is when returning a ``NULL`` pointer. "
"When using bindings, the returned pointer will be ``NULL`` (a global "
"singleton with a wrapped pointer of 0) rather than ``null`` (the JavaScript "
"built-in object) or 0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:498
msgid "void*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:500
msgid ""
"The ``void*`` type is supported through a ``VoidPtr`` type that you can use "
"in IDL files. You can also use the ``any`` type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/WebIDL-Binder.rst:502
msgid ""
"The difference between them is that ``VoidPtr`` behaves like a pointer type "
"in that you get a wrapper object, while ``any`` behaves like a 32-bit "
"integer (which is what raw pointers are in Emscripten-compiled code)."
msgstr ""

